(21, 'CRITICAL', 'Loan Portfolio', '[AUTO-C08] Loan Portfolio Quality\n\n3 delinquent loan(s) outstanding. Delinquent amount: 1,000,000 FCFA.', 'WHAT: One or more loans are delinquent — the borrower has missed scheduled repayment deadlines. Delinquent loans represent a direct financial risk to the bank.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Delinquent loans reduce the bank&#039;s income, increase provisioning costs, and can lead to write-offs if not managed. High delinquency rates also signal weakness in credit underwriting.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each delinquent loan — check the borrower&#039;s payment history, collateral, and communication records. (2) Contact each borrower to understand why payments are late and negotiate a repayment plan. (3) For high-value delinquencies, escalate to the collections team or legal department. (4) Assess collateral coverage — if insufficient, increase provisions. (5) Review the loan origination process to identify underwriting weaknesses that allowed these delinquencies.\n\nWHO: Credit Risk Manager / Head of Lending', 'All Branches', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-23', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 12:19:42'),
(22, 'HIGH', 'Loan Portfolio', '[AUTO-DS02] Suspicious Loan Amount Clustering\n\nMultiple active loans share identical disbursement amounts. While some overlap is normal (e.g., standardized loan products), a high concentration of identical amounts can indicate cloned applications, templated lending without proper risk assessment, or batch processing anomalies.\n\nDetected patterns (top 5): 0 FCFA (4 loans)\n\nTotal pattern groups: 1. This pattern requires investigation to rule out fraud or policy violations.', 'WHAT: Several groups of active loans were disbursed with identical amounts. This clustering pattern is unusual and may indicate cloned loan applications or templated processing.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Loan amount clustering can be a sign of fraud — borrowers may be colluding to submit identical applications, or staff may be bypassing individual credit assessments by reusing the same loan template. This exposes the bank to concentration risk and credit losses.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Cross-reference the affected loans for borrower relationships — same employer, same guarantor, same address, or same phone number. (2) Verify each loan went through an independent credit assessment with proper documentation. (3) Check if the disbursement amounts correspond to standard loan products — if not, investigate further. (4) Escalate to the fraud investigation team if borrower collusion is suspected. (5) Review the loan origination process to ensure each application is assessed individually.\n\nWHO: Credit Risk Manager / Fraud Investigation Team', 'All Branches', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-23', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-04-23 19:51:29'),
(23, 'MEDIUM', 'Transaction Monitoring', '[AUTO-DS03] Off-Hours Transaction Activity\n\n104 transactions were posted outside normal business hours (before 6AM or after 6PM UTC). While some off-hours activity is expected — such as ATM withdrawals, mobile banking transfers, and automated batch processing — a high volume of off-hours transactions warrants review to ensure all activity is legitimate and properly authorized.\n\nMost recent off-hours transactions:\nTXN-20260423-0028 — 1 000 000 FCFA at 2026-04-23 20:27:38\nTXN-20260422-0053 — 100 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:48:23\nTXN-20260422-0052 — 3 767 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:44\nTXN-20260422-0051 — 200 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:43\nTXN-20260422-0050 — 200 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:41\nTXN-20260422-0049 — 200 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:40\nTXN-20260422-0048 — 200 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:39\nTXN-20260422-0047 — 200 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:38\nTXN-20260422-0046 — 1 000 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:21\nTXN-20260422-0045 — 6 935 FCFA at 2026-04-22 21:28:49', 'WHAT: A significant number of transactions were posted outside normal business hours.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Off-hours transactions can be a sign of unauthorized access, after-hours manipulation of accounts, or automated processing errors. While many off-hours transactions are legitimate (ATMs, mobile banking, batch jobs), the volume detected exceeds typical patterns and should be reviewed.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each off-hours transaction to determine the channel (ATM, mobile, branch, batch). (2) For branch-initiated transactions outside business hours, verify the authorization and identify the staff member who posted them. (3) If batch processing explains the volume, document the batch schedule and verify all batch jobs are authorized. (4) Implement channel-specific monitoring so ATM and mobile transactions are separated from staff-initiated ones. (5) Set up alerts for staff-initiated transactions posted outside business hours.\n\nWHO: Branch Operations Manager / IT Security Officer', 'All Branches', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-23', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-04-23 19:51:30'),
