(35, 'CRITICAL', 'Loan Portfolio', '[AUTO-C08] Loan Portfolio Quality\n\n3 delinquent loan(s) outstanding. Delinquent amount: 1,000,000 FCFA.', 'WHAT: One or more loans are delinquent — the borrower has missed scheduled repayment deadlines. Delinquent loans represent a direct financial risk to the bank.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Delinquent loans reduce the bank&#039;s income, increase provisioning costs, and can lead to write-offs if not managed. High delinquency rates also signal weakness in credit underwriting.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each delinquent loan — check the borrower&#039;s payment history, collateral, and communication records. (2) Contact each borrower to understand why payments are late and negotiate a repayment plan. (3) For high-value delinquencies, escalate to the collections team or legal department. (4) Assess collateral coverage — if insufficient, increase provisions. (5) Review the loan origination process to identify underwriting weaknesses that allowed these delinquencies.\n\nWHO: Credit Risk Manager / Head of Lending', 'All Branches', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-25', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 12:19:40'),
(36, 'HIGH', 'Reconciliation', '[AUTO-C11] Operating Fund vs GL Reconciliation\n\nOpFund net: 479,697,302 / GL 1400: 479,591,906 FCFA. Discrepancy: 105,396 FCFA.', 'WHAT: The Operating Fund balance does not match the balance shown in GL account 1400 (Cash and Banks). These two figures should always be identical.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: A discrepancy between the operating fund and its GL account means your cash position is misstated. This can lead to incorrect liquidity management, failed payments, or undetected losses.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Compare the operating fund transaction history against GL entries for account 1400. (2) Identify any transaction recorded in one system but not the other — common causes include manual GL adjustments not reflected in the operating fund, or fund transfers posted outside the normal workflow. (3) Post correcting entries to bring both sides into agreement. (4) Ensure all future fund movements are posted simultaneously to both systems. (5) Run this reconciliation daily as part of the end-of-day process.\n\nWHO: Head of Accounts / Treasury Manager', 'All Branches', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-25', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 12:19:41'),
(37, 'MEDIUM', 'Compliance', '[AUTO-C13] Pending Approvals Queue\n\n5 pending approval(s) require attention.', 'WHAT: Some approval requests are waiting for a decision. Pending approvals can delay operations, loans, expenses, and other critical processes.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Delayed approvals create bottlenecks that slow down business operations, frustrate staff, and can lead to missed deadlines or regulatory non-compliance.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review all pending approvals and prioritize by urgency and risk level. (2) Process or delegate each approval without delay. (3) If any approval has been pending for an unusually long time, escalate to the next level of management. (4) Identify the root cause of the backlog — is it understaffing, unclear authority, or process inefficiency? (5) Set up SLA-based alerts so management is notified when approvals exceed acceptable timeframes.\n\nWHO: Branch Manager / Department Heads', 'All Branches', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-25', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 09:17:35'),
(38, 'HIGH', 'Loan Portfolio', '[AUTO-DS02] Suspicious Loan Amount Clustering\n\nMultiple active loans share identical disbursement amounts. While some overlap is normal (e.g., standardized loan products), a high concentration of identical amounts can indicate cloned applications, templated lending without proper risk assessment, or batch processing anomalies.\n\nDetected patterns (top 5): 1 000 000 FCFA (3 loans)\n\nTotal pattern groups: 1. This pattern requires investigation to rule out fraud or policy violations.', 'WHAT: Several groups of active loans were disbursed with identical amounts. This clustering pattern is unusual and may indicate cloned loan applications or templated processing.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Loan amount clustering can be a sign of fraud — borrowers may be colluding to submit identical applications, or staff may be bypassing individual credit assessments by reusing the same loan template. This exposes the bank to concentration risk and credit losses.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Cross-reference the affected loans for borrower relationships — same employer, same guarantor, same address, or same phone number. (2) Verify each loan went through an independent credit assessment with proper documentation. (3) Check if the disbursement amounts correspond to standard loan products — if not, investigate further. (4) Escalate to the fraud investigation team if borrower collusion is suspected. (5) Review the loan origination process to ensure each application is assessed individually.\n\nWHO: Credit Risk Manager / Fraud Investigation Team', 'All Branches', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-25', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-04-25 07:39:15'),
(39, 'MEDIUM', 'Transaction Monitoring', '[AUTO-DS03] Off-Hours Transaction Activity\n\n109 transactions were posted outside normal business hours (before 6AM or after 6PM UTC). While some off-hours activity is expected — such as ATM withdrawals, mobile banking transfers, and automated batch processing — a high volume of off-hours transactions warrants review to ensure all activity is legitimate and properly authorized.\n\nMost recent off-hours transactions:\nTXN-20260425-0001 — 100 000 FCFA at 2026-04-24 23:02:04\nTXN-20260423-0032 — 100 000 FCFA at 2026-04-23 22:39:15\nTXN-20260423-0031 — 1 000 000 FCFA at 2026-04-23 21:55:54\nTXN-20260423-0030 — 2 000 000 FCFA at 2026-04-23 21:35:32\nTXN-20260423-0029 — 1 000 000 FCFA at 2026-04-23 21:34:13\nTXN-20260423-0028 — 1 000 000 FCFA at 2026-04-23 20:27:38\nTXN-20260422-0053 — 100 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:48:23\nTXN-20260422-0052 — 3 767 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:44\nTXN-20260422-0051 — 200 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:43\nTXN-20260422-0050 — 200 000 FCFA at 2026-04-22 22:17:41', 'WHAT: A significant number of transactions were posted outside normal business hours.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Off-hours transactions can be a sign of unauthorized access, after-hours manipulation of accounts, or automated processing errors. While many off-hours transactions are legitimate (ATMs, mobile banking, batch jobs), the volume detected exceeds typical patterns and should be reviewed.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each off-hours transaction to determine the channel (ATM, mobile, branch, batch). (2) For branch-initiated transactions outside business hours, verify the authorization and identify the staff member who posted them. (3) If batch processing explains the volume, document the batch schedule and verify all batch jobs are authorized. (4) Implement channel-specific monitoring so ATM and mobile transactions are separated from staff-initiated ones. (5) Set up alerts for staff-initiated transactions posted outside business hours.\n\nWHO: Branch Operations Manager / IT Security Officer', 'All Branches', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-25', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-04-25 07:39:15'),
(40, 'HIGH', 'Compliance', '[AUTO-C06] Customer KYC Completeness\n\n5 customer(s) have incomplete KYC data.', 'WHAT: Some customers have incomplete Know Your Customer (KYC) records. KYC is a regulatory requirement that helps verify customer identity and prevent money laundering.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Incomplete KYC is a regulatory violation that can result in fines, sanctions, or license suspension. It also increases the risk of fraud and money laundering.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Generate a list of all customers with incomplete KYC from the Customer Management module. (2) Contact each customer to request missing documents (ID card, proof of address, etc.). (3) Set a deadline — typically 30 days — for customers to provide the required documents. (4) If the deadline passes without compliance, restrict the account (limit transactions or freeze it). (5) Update the account opening process to enforce mandatory KYC fields before activation.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / Branch Operations Manager', 'KUMBA', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-25', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 14:15:27'),
(41, 'CRITICAL', 'Loan Portfolio', '[AUTO-C08] Loan Portfolio Quality\n\n3 delinquent loan(s). Amount: 1 000 000 FCFA.', 'WHAT: One or more loans are delinquent — the borrower has missed scheduled repayment deadlines. Delinquent loans represent a direct financial risk to the bank.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Delinquent loans reduce the bank&#039;s income, increase provisioning costs, and can lead to write-offs if not managed. High delinquency rates also signal weakness in credit underwriting.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each delinquent loan — check the borrower&#039;s payment history, collateral, and communication records. (2) Contact each borrower to understand why payments are late and negotiate a repayment plan. (3) For high-value delinquencies, escalate to the collections team or legal department. (4) Assess collateral coverage — if insufficient, increase provisions. (5) Review the loan origination process to identify underwriting weaknesses that allowed these delinquencies.\n\nWHO: Credit Risk Manager / Head of Lending', 'KUMBA', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-25', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-04-25 21:08:28'),
(42, 'MEDIUM', 'Access Control', '[AUTO-C12] Staff Access Control\n\n0 active staff out of 2. 2 inactive — verify access revoked.', 'WHAT: Some staff members are marked as INACTIVE but may still have system access. Former or inactive employees should not be able to log in or perform transactions.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Active system access for former employees is a serious security risk. It can lead to unauthorized transactions, data breaches, or regulatory violations related to access control.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Cross-reference the staff list with the system access logs. (2) For each inactive staff member, verify their login has been disabled and their permissions revoked. (3) Contact HR to confirm the employment status of any inactive staff who still appear to have recent system activity. (4) Implement automatic access revocation triggered by HR status changes. (5) Conduct a quarterly access review to catch any gaps.\n\nWHO: IT Systems Administrator / HR Manager', 'KUMBA', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-25', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 14:15:28'),
