 Operations Manager / IT Security Officer', 'All Branches', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-27', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-04-27 10:21:51'),
(142, 'LOW', 'Risk Management', '[AUTO-DS06] Customers with Multiple Active Accounts\n\n1 customer(s) hold 3 or more active accounts. While having multiple accounts is common for business customers or customers with different product types (savings, current, fixed deposit), a high number of accounts per customer can be used to circumvent transaction monitoring limits, split large transfers below reporting thresholds, or obscure the true volume of activity.\n\nCustomers: 7 (3 accounts)', 'WHAT: Some customers hold 3 or more active accounts.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Multiple accounts per customer can be used to structure transactions below reporting thresholds (&quot;smurfing&quot;), circumvent daily limits, or obscure the total relationship. This is a red flag for anti-money laundering (AML) compliance.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each multi-account customer to verify the accounts serve distinct, legitimate purposes. (2) Aggregate transaction activity across all accounts for each customer to get the true picture. (3) If structuring patterns are detected, file a Suspicious Transaction Report (STR). (4) Consider implementing a customer-level transaction monitoring view instead of account-level only. (5) Set a policy requiring additional approval for customers requesting more than 3 active accounts.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / AML Analyst', 'All Branches', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-27', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-04-27 10:21:51'),
(143, 'MEDIUM', 'Compliance', '[AUTO-C16] Profit Ledger Activity\n\n0 profit ledger entries across 0 category(ies). Total fee income: 0 FCFA.', 'WHAT: The Profit Ledger records fee income from various banking activities. This check verifies that fee income is being properly recorded.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Fee income is a significant revenue source. If fees are not being recorded, the bank is underreporting revenue, which affects profitability analysis and regulatory reporting.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Check which fee categories have entries in the Profit Ledger. (2) Verify that all fee-bearing products (loan processing fees, account maintenance fees, transfer fees, ATM fees) are generating ledger entries. (3) If a category is missing, investigate whether the fee posting automation is working. (4) Manually post any missing fee entries with proper supporting documentation. (5) Test the fee automation by processing a test transaction and verifying it appears in the ledger.\n\nWHO: Head of Accounts / Finance Manager', 'LIMBE', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-27', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-04-27 12:42:11'),
(144, 'HIGH', 'Compliance', '[AUTO-C06] Customer KYC Completeness\n\n2 customer(s) have incomplete KYC data.', 'WHAT: Some customers have incomplete Know Your Customer (KYC) records. KYC is a regulatory requirement that helps verify customer identity and prevent money laundering.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Incomplete KYC is a regulatory violation that can result in fines, sanctions, or license suspension. It also increases the risk of fraud and money laundering.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Generate a list of all customers with incomplete KYC from the Customer Management module. (2) Contact each customer to request missing documents (ID card, proof of address, etc.). (3) Set a deadline — typically 30 days — for customers to provide the required documents. (4) If the deadline passes without compliance, restrict the account (limit transactions or freeze it). (5) Update the account opening process to enforce mandatory KYC fields before activation.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / Branch Operations Manager', 'LIMBE', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-27', 'Financial Ratios', NULL, '2026-04-27 12:43:03'),
(145, 'MEDIUM', 'Access Control', '[AUTO-C12] Staff Access Control\n\n0 active staff out of 1. 1 inactive — verify access revoked.', 'WHAT: Some staff members are marked as INACTIVE but may still have system access. Former or inactive employees should not be able to log in or perform transactions.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Active system access for former employees is a serious security risk. It can lead to unauthorized transactions, data breaches, or regulatory violations related to access control.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Cross-reference the staff list with the system access logs. (2) For each inactive staff member, verify their login has been disabled and their permissions revoked. (3) Contact HR to confirm the employment status of any inactive staff who still appear to have recent system activity. (4) Implement automatic access revocation triggered by HR status changes. (5) Conduct a quarterly access review to catch any gaps.\n\nWHO: IT Systems Administrator / HR Manager', 'LIMBE', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-27', 'Financial Ratios', NULL, '2026-04-27 12:42:50'),
(146, 'HIGH', 'Risk Management', '[AUTO-C17] Loan-to-Deposit Ratio\n\nLDR is 0% (loans: 0 / deposits: 1 100 000 FCFA). Below optimal range.', 'WHAT: The Loan-to-Deposit Ratio (LDR) measures how much of the bank&#039;s customer deposits have been lent out. A healthy range is typically 30% to 90%.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: If the LDR is above 90%, the bank may not have enough liquidity to meet withdrawal demands. If below 30%, the bank is not using its deposit base efficiently to generate interest income.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) If LDR is above 90%: Reduce new lending, increase deposit mobilization campaigns, or consider securitizing some loans. (2) If LDR is below 30%: Review the lending strategy for growth opportunities, relax qualifying criteria where appropriate, or launch targeted loan products. (3) Set up automated alerts when the ratio approaches 80% or drops below 35%. (4) Review the LDR monthly as part of the Asset-Liability Committee (ALCO) process.\n\nWHO: Chief Risk Officer / Treasury Manager', 'LIMBE', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-04-27', 'Financial Ratios', NULL, '2026-04-27 12:42:28'),
(147, 'HIGH', 'Transaction Monitoring', '[AUTO-C09] Large Transaction Monitoring (&gt;5M FCFA)\n\n1 large transaction(s) detected (top: TXN-20260503-0162 — 20 000 000 FCFA).', 'WHAT: Transactions exceeding 5,000,000 FCFA were detected. Large transactions require enhanced monitoring under Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Large transactions can be indicative of money laundering, terrorist financing, or other illicit activity. Regulations require banks to monitor, document, and report such transactions.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each large transaction — verify it has proper authorization, supporting documentation (invoices, contracts), and a clear business purpose. (2) Cross-reference the parties involved against sanctions lists and PEP (Politically Exposed Person) databases. (3) If the transaction appears suspicious, file a Suspicious Transaction Report (STR) with the relevant authority. (4) Ensure Large Transaction Reports (LTR) are filed as required by regulation. (5) Set up automated alerts for future transactions above this threshold.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / AML Analyst', 'LIMBE', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-03', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 14:02:23'),
(148, 'HIGH', 'Loan Portfolio', '[AUTO-DS02] Suspicious Loan Amount Clustering\n\nMultiple active loans share identical disbursement amounts. While some overlap is normal (e.g., standardized loan products), a high concentration of identical amounts can indicate cloned applications, templated lending without proper risk assessment, or batch processing anomalies.\n\nDetected patterns (top 5): 1 000 000 FCFA (4 loans)\n\nTotal pattern groups: 1. This pattern requires investigation to rule out fraud or policy violations.', 'WHAT: Several groups of active loans were disbursed with identical amounts. This clustering pattern is unusual and may indicate cloned loan applications or templated processing.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Loan amount clustering can be a sign of fraud — borrowers may be colluding to submit identical applications, or staff may be bypassing individual credit assessments by reusing the same loan template. This exposes the bank to concentration risk and credit losses.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Cross-reference the affected loans for borrower relationships — same employer, same guarantor, same address, or same phone number. (2) Verify each loan went through an independent credit assessment with proper documentation. (3) Check if the disbursement amounts correspond to standard loan products — if not, investigate further. (4) Escalate to the fraud investigation team if borrower collusion is suspected. (5) Review the loan origination process to ensure each application is assessed individually.\n\nWHO: Credit Risk Manager / Fraud Investigation Team', 'LIMBE', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-03', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 12:19:30'),
(149, 'HIGH', 'Transaction Monitoring', '[AUTO-DS08] Potential Layering Activity Detected\n\n1 account(s) show patterns of 4 or more deposits within a 60-minute window. This pattern is consistent with &quot;layering&quot; — a stage of money laundering where illicit funds are broken into multiple smaller deposits in rapid succession to obscure the origin of the money and avoid triggering transaction reporting thresholds.\n\nThis is a high-severity finding that requires immediate review by the compliance team.', 'WHAT: Multiple accounts received 4 or more deposits within 60 minutes, a pattern consistent with money laundering layering.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Layering is the second stage of money laundering, where criminals break large sums into many small transactions to avoid detection. If this pattern is confirmed, the bank may be processing illicit funds and faces regulatory penalties, reputational damage, and potential criminal liability.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Immediately freeze the affected accounts pending investigation — do NOT alert the account holders. (2) Review the full transaction history of each account for the past 90 days. (3) Identify the source of funds for each deposit — are they from the same originator? (4) Cross-reference account holders against sanctions lists and PEP databases. (5) File Suspicious Transaction Reports (STR) with the relevant financial intelligence unit. (6) If confirmed, cooperate with law enforcement as required.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / AML Analyst / MLRO (Money Laundering Reporting Officer)', 'LIMBE', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-03', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 12:19:30'),
(150, 'HIGH', 'Transaction Monitoring', '[AUTO-DS08] Potential Layering Activity Detected\n\n1 account(s) show patterns of 4 or more deposits within a 60-minute window. This pattern is consistent with &quot;layering&quot; — a stage of money laundering where illicit funds are broken into multiple smaller deposits in rapid succession to obscure the origin of the money and avoid triggering transaction reporting thresholds.\n\nThis is a high-severity finding that requires immediate review by the compliance team.', 'WHAT: Multiple accounts received 4 or more deposits within 60 minutes, a pattern consistent with money laundering layering.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Layering is the second stage of money laundering, where criminals break large sums into many small transactions to avoid detection. If this pattern is confirmed, the bank may be processing illicit funds and faces regulatory penalties, reputational damage, and potential criminal liability.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Immediately freeze the affected accounts pending investigation — do NOT alert the account holders. (2) Review the full transaction history of each account for the past 90 days. (3) Identify the source of funds for each deposit — are they from the same originator? (4) Cross-reference account holders against sanctions lists and PEP databases. (5) File Suspicious Transaction Reports (STR) with the relevant financial intelligence unit. (6) If confirmed, cooperate with law enforcement as required.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / AML Analyst / MLRO (Money Laundering Reporting Officer)', 'All Branches', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-03', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 12:19:43'),
(151, 'CRITICAL', 'Loan Portfolio', '[AUTO-C08] Loan Portfolio Quality\n\n3 delinquent loan(s). Amount: 1 000 000 FCFA.', 'WHAT: One or more loans are delinquent — the borrower has missed scheduled repayment deadlines. Delinquent loans represent a direct financial risk to the bank.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Delinquent loans reduce the bank&#039;s income, increase provisioning costs, and can lead to write-offs if not managed. High delinquency rates also signal weakness in credit underwriting.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each delinquent loan — check the borrower&#039;s payment history, collateral, and communication records. (2) Contact each borrower to understand why payments are late and negotiate a repayment plan. (3) For high-value delinquencies, escalate to the collections team or legal department. (4) Assess collateral coverage — if insufficient, increase provisions. (5) Review the loan origination process to identify underwriting weaknesses that allowed these delinquencies.\n\nWHO: Credit Risk Manager / Head of Lending', 'KUMBA', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-03', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 14:02:39'),
(152, 'LOW', 'Risk Management', '[AUTO-DS06] Customers with Multiple Active Accounts\n\n1 customer(s) hold 3 or more active accounts. While having multiple accounts is common for business customers or customers with different product types (savings, current, fixed deposit), a high number of accounts per customer can be used to circumvent transaction monitoring limits, split large transfers below reporting thresholds, or obscure the true volume of activity.\n\nCustomers: 7 (3 accounts)', 'WHAT: Some customers hold 3 or more active accounts.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Multiple accounts per customer can be used to structure transactions below reporting thresholds (&quot;smurfing&quot;), circumvent daily limits, or obscure the total relationship. This is a red flag for anti-money laundering (AML) compliance.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each multi-account customer to verify the accounts serve distinct, legitimate purposes. (2) Aggregate transaction activity across all accounts for each customer to get the true picture. (3) If structuring patterns are detected, file a Suspicious Transaction Report (STR). (4) Consider implementing a customer-level transaction monitoring view instead of account-level only. (5) Set a policy requiring additional approval for customers requesting more than 3 active accounts.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / AML Analyst', 'KUMBA', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-03', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 14:02:23'),
(153, 'CRITICAL', 'Loan Portfolio', '[AUTO-C08] Loan Portfolio Quality\n\n3 delinquent loan(s) outstanding. Delinquent amount: 1,000,000 FCFA.', 'WHAT: One or more loans are delinquent — the borrower has missed scheduled repayment deadlines. Delinquent loans represent a direct financial risk to the bank.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Delinquent loans reduce the bank&#039;s income, increase provisioning costs, and can lead to write-offs if not managed. High delinquency rates also signal weakness in credit underwriting.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each delinquent loan — check the borrower&#039;s payment history, collateral, and communication records. (2) Contact each borrower to understand why payments are late and negotiate a repayment plan. (3) For high-value delinquencies, escalate to the collections team or legal department. (4) Assess collateral coverage — if insufficient, increase provisions. (5) Review the loan origination process to identify underwriting weaknesses that allowed these delinquencies.\n\nWHO: Credit Risk Manager / Head of Lending', 'KUMBA', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-03', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 14:15:26'),
(154, 'HIGH', 'Reconciliation', '[AUTO-C11] Operating Fund vs GL Reconciliation\n\nOpFund net: 349,955,000 / GL 1400: 349,928,651 FCFA. Discrepancy: 26,349 FCFA.', 'WHAT: The Operating Fund balance does not match the balance shown in GL account 1400 (Cash and Banks). These two figures should always be identical.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: A discrepancy between the operating fund and its GL account means your cash position is misstated. This can lead to incorrect liquidity management, failed payments, or undetected losses.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Compare the operating fund transaction history against GL entries for account 1400. (2) Identify any transaction recorded in one system but not the other — common causes include manual GL adjustments not reflected in the operating fund, or fund transfers posted outside the normal workflow. (3) Post correcting entries to bring both sides into agreement. (4) Ensure all future fund movements are posted simultaneously to both systems. (5) Run this reconciliation daily as part of the end-of-day process.\n\nWHO: Head of Accounts / Treasury Manager', 'KUMBA', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-03', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 14:15:26'),
(155, 'HIGH', 'Risk Management', '[AUTO-C17] Loan-to-Deposit Ratio\n\nLDR is 582.7% (loans: 25,611,453 / deposits: 4,395,000 FCFA). Exceeds 90% regulatory threshold.', 'WHAT: The Loan-to-Deposit Ratio (LDR) measures how much of the bank&#039;s customer deposits have been lent out. A healthy range is typically 30% to 90%.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: If the LDR is above 90%, the bank may not have enough liquidity to meet withdrawal demands. If below 30%, the bank is not using its deposit base efficiently to generate interest income.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) If LDR is above 90%: Reduce new lending, increase deposit mobilization campaigns, or consider securitizing some loans. (2) If LDR is below 30%: Review the lending strategy for growth opportunities, relax qualifying criteria where appropriate, or launch targeted loan products. (3) Set up automated alerts when the ratio approaches 80% or drops below 35%. (4) Review the LDR monthly as part of the Asset-Liability Committee (ALCO) process.\n\nWHO: Chief Risk Officer / Treasury Manager', 'LIMBE', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-03', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-03 14:15:50'),
(156, 'MEDIUM', 'Expense Management', '[AUTO-DS05] High-Value Expense Items Detected\n\nThe following approved expenses exceed the 1,000,000 FCFA monitoring threshold. While approved expenses are not necessarily improper, high-value items require enhanced scrutiny to ensure they were properly authorized, documented, and aligned with the bank&#039;s budget.\n\nTop 3 largest approved expenses:\npurchase of pc — 1 200 000 FCFA (KUMBA)\nbill payment — 120 000 FCFA (All Branches)\nbill — 50 000 FCFA (LIMBE)\n\nTotal approved expenses: 1 471 349 FCFA across 7 records.', 'WHAT: One or more approved expenses exceed the 1,000,000 FCFA monitoring threshold.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: High-value expenses are a common area for fraud, waste, and abuse. Even when properly approved, large expenses can strain the budget and should be verified against actual business needs and supporting documentation.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Obtain receipts, invoices, and contracts for each high-value expense. (2) Verify the approval was made by someone with the appropriate authority level for that amount. (3) Cross-reference the expense against the budget to ensure it was allocated. (4) If any expense lacks proper documentation, escalate to management for review. (5) Consider lowering the monitoring threshold if the volume of high-value expenses is concerning.\n\nWHO: Finance Manager / Internal Audit', 'All Branches', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-04', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-04 16:32:02'),
(157, 'MEDIUM', 'Expense Management', '[AUTO-DS05] High-Value Expense Items Detected\n\nThe following approved expenses exceed the 1,000,000 FCFA monitoring threshold. While approved expenses are not necessarily improper, high-value items require enhanced scrutiny to ensure they were properly authorized, documented, and aligned with the bank&#039;s budget.\n\nTop 3 largest approved expenses:\npurchase of pc — 1 200 000 FCFA (KUMBA)\nBILL — 45 000 FCFA (KUMBA)\npayment of bill — 26 349 FCFA (KUMBA)\n\nTotal approved expenses: 1 271 349 FCFA across 3 records.', 'WHAT: One or more approved expenses exceed the 1,000,000 FCFA monitoring threshold.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: High-value expenses are a common area for fraud, waste, and abuse. Even when properly approved, large expenses can strain the budget and should be verified against actual business needs and supporting documentation.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Obtain receipts, invoices, and contracts for each high-value expense. (2) Verify the approval was made by someone with the appropriate authority level for that amount. (3) Cross-reference the expense against the budget to ensure it was allocated. (4) If any expense lacks proper documentation, escalate to management for review. (5) Consider lowering the monitoring threshold if the volume of high-value expenses is concerning.\n\nWHO: Finance Manager / Internal Audit', 'KUMBA', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-04', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-04 16:32:10'),
(158, 'MEDIUM', 'Compliance', '[AUTO-C16] Profit Ledger Activity\n\n0 profit ledger entries across 0 category(ies). Total fee income: 0 FCFA.', 'WHAT: The Profit Ledger records fee income from various banking activities. This check verifies that fee income is being properly recorded.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Fee income is a significant revenue source. If fees are not being recorded, the bank is underreporting revenue, which affects profitability analysis and regulatory reporting.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Check which fee categories have entries in the Profit Ledger. (2) Verify that all fee-bearing products (loan processing fees, account maintenance fees, transfer fees, ATM fees) are generating ledger entries. (3) If a category is missing, investigate whether the fee posting automation is working. (4) Manually post any missing fee entries with proper supporting documentation. (5) Test the fee automation by processing a test transaction and verifying it appears in the ledger.\n\nWHO: Head of Accounts / Finance Manager', 'BAFOUSSAM', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-04', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-04 20:56:02'),
(159, 'HIGH', 'Risk Management', '[AUTO-C17] Loan-to-Deposit Ratio\n\nLDR is 0.0% (loans: 0 / deposits: 0 FCFA). Below optimal range (30-90%).', 'WHAT: The Loan-to-Deposit Ratio (LDR) measures how much of the bank&#039;s customer deposits have been lent out. A healthy range is typically 30% to 90%.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: If the LDR is above 90%, the bank may not have enough liquidity to meet withdrawal demands. If below 30%, the bank is not using its deposit base efficiently to generate interest income.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) If LDR is above 90%: Reduce new lending, increase deposit mobilization campaigns, or consider securitizing some loans. (2) If LDR is below 30%: Review the lending strategy for growth opportunities, relax qualifying criteria where appropriate, or launch targeted loan products. (3) Set up automated alerts when the ratio approaches 80% or drops below 35%. (4) Review the LDR monthly as part of the Asset-Liability Committee (ALCO) process.\n\nWHO: Chief Risk Officer / Treasury Manager', 'BAFOUSSAM', 'CLOSED', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-04', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-06 11:13:12'),
