(161, 'HIGH', 'Risk Management', '[AUTO-C17] Loan-to-Deposit Ratio\n\nLDR is 0.0% (loans: 0 / deposits: 0 FCFA). Below optimal range (30-90%).', 'WHAT: The Loan-to-Deposit Ratio (LDR) measures how much of the bank&#039;s customer deposits have been lent out. A healthy range is typically 30% to 90%.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: If the LDR is above 90%, the bank may not have enough liquidity to meet withdrawal demands. If below 30%, the bank is not using its deposit base efficiently to generate interest income.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) If LDR is above 90%: Reduce new lending, increase deposit mobilization campaigns, or consider securitizing some loans. (2) If LDR is below 30%: Review the lending strategy for growth opportunities, relax qualifying criteria where appropriate, or launch targeted loan products. (3) Set up automated alerts when the ratio approaches 80% or drops below 35%. (4) Review the LDR monthly as part of the Asset-Liability Committee (ALCO) process.\n\nWHO: Chief Risk Officer / Treasury Manager', 'EDEA', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-06', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-06 10:58:35');
INSERT INTO "audit_findings" ("id", "severity", "category", "description", "recommendation", "branch", "status", "assignee", "created_date", "created_by", "updated_at", "timestamp") VALUES
(162, 'MEDIUM', 'Transaction Monitoring', '[AUTO-DS03] Off-Hours Transaction Activity\n\n6 transactions were posted outside normal business hours (before 6AM or after 6PM UTC). While some off-hours activity is expected — such as ATM withdrawals, mobile banking transfers, and automated batch processing — a high volume of off-hours transactions warrants review to ensure all activity is legitimate and properly authorized.\n\nMost recent off-hours transactions:\nTXN-20260505-0004 — 200 000 FCFA at 2026-05-05 00:48:09\nTXN-20260505-0003 — 2 000 000 FCFA at 2026-05-04 23:36:50\nTXN-20260505-0002 — 2 000 000 FCFA at 2026-05-04 23:34:56\nTXN-20260505-0001 — 2 000 000 FCFA at 2026-05-04 23:01:21\nTXN-20260504-0054 — 2 000 000 FCFA at 2026-05-04 22:39:02\nTXN-20260504-0053 — 1 000 000 FCFA at 2026-05-04 21:57:38', 'WHAT: A significant number of transactions were posted outside normal business hours.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Off-hours transactions can be a sign of unauthorized access, after-hours manipulation of accounts, or automated processing errors. While many off-hours transactions are legitimate (ATMs, mobile banking, batch jobs), the volume detected exceeds typical patterns and should be reviewed.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each off-hours transaction to determine the channel (ATM, mobile, branch, batch). (2) For branch-initiated transactions outside business hours, verify the authorization and identify the staff member who posted them. (3) If batch processing explains the volume, document the batch schedule and verify all batch jobs are authorized. (4) Implement channel-specific monitoring so ATM and mobile transactions are separated from staff-initiated ones. (5) Set up alerts for staff-initiated transactions posted outside business hours.\n\nWHO: Branch Operations Manager / IT Security Officer', 'BAFOUSSAM', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-06', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-06 11:13:13'),
(163, 'MEDIUM', 'Risk Management', '[AUTO-DS01] Active Accounts with Zero Balance\n\n5 customer accounts are currently marked as ACTIVE but have a ledger balance of zero. While some of these may be newly opened accounts that have not yet received funds, a large number of zero-balance active accounts can indicate dormant accounts that were never properly reclassified, or accounts created for purposes other than legitimate banking.\n\nAffected accounts (first 10): ACC-200100018, ACC-200100016, ACC-200100014, ACC-200100015, ACC-200100013', 'WHAT: A significant number of active accounts have zero balance. These accounts may be dormant, unused, or potentially created for illegitimate purposes.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Zero-balance active accounts that are not properly classified can be exploited for money laundering or used to circumvent transaction monitoring. They also inflate active account counts, giving a false picture of the bank&#039;s customer base.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each zero-balance account to determine when it was opened and whether any transaction has ever occurred. (2) Contact account holders to confirm their intention to use the account. (3) Reclassify accounts with no activity for 90+ days as DORMANT per bank policy. (4) Close accounts that customers confirm are no longer needed. (5) Implement automated dormancy detection that flags accounts with zero balance and no transactions for 60+ days.\n\nWHO: Branch Operations Manager / Compliance Officer', 'LIMBE', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-06', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-06 11:13:17'),
(164, 'HIGH', 'Loan Portfolio', '[AUTO-DS02] Suspicious Loan Amount Clustering\n\nMultiple active loans share identical disbursement amounts. While some overlap is normal (e.g., standardized loan products), a high concentration of identical amounts can indicate cloned applications, templated lending without proper risk assessment, or batch processing anomalies.\n\nDetected patterns (top 5): 1 000 000 FCFA (4 loans)\n\nTotal pattern groups: 1. This pattern requires investigation to rule out fraud or policy violations.', 'WHAT: Several groups of active loans were disbursed with identical amounts. This clustering pattern is unusual and may indicate cloned loan applications or templated processing.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Loan amount clustering can be a sign of fraud — borrowers may be colluding to submit identical applications, or staff may be bypassing individual credit assessments by reusing the same loan template. This exposes the bank to concentration risk and credit losses.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Cross-reference the affected loans for borrower relationships — same employer, same guarantor, same address, or same phone number. (2) Verify each loan went through an independent credit assessment with proper documentation. (3) Check if the disbursement amounts correspond to standard loan products — if not, investigate further. (4) Escalate to the fraud investigation team if borrower collusion is suspected. (5) Review the loan origination process to ensure each application is assessed individually.\n\nWHO: Credit Risk Manager / Fraud Investigation Team', 'LIMBE', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-06', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-06 11:13:18'),
(165, 'LOW', 'Risk Management', '[AUTO-DS06] Customers with Multiple Active Accounts\n\n1 customer(s) hold 3 or more active accounts. While having multiple accounts is common for business customers or customers with different product types (savings, current, fixed deposit), a high number of accounts per customer can be used to circumvent transaction monitoring limits, split large transfers below reporting thresholds, or obscure the true volume of activity.\n\nCustomers: 11 (3 accounts)', 'WHAT: Some customers hold 3 or more active accounts.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Multiple accounts per customer can be used to structure transactions below reporting thresholds (&quot;smurfing&quot;), circumvent daily limits, or obscure the total relationship. This is a red flag for anti-money laundering (AML) compliance.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each multi-account customer to verify the accounts serve distinct, legitimate purposes. (2) Aggregate transaction activity across all accounts for each customer to get the true picture. (3) If structuring patterns are detected, file a Suspicious Transaction Report (STR). (4) Consider implementing a customer-level transaction monitoring view instead of account-level only. (5) Set a policy requiring additional approval for customers requesting more than 3 active accounts.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / AML Analyst', 'LIMBE', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-06', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-06 11:13:19'),
(166, 'HIGH', 'Transaction Monitoring', '[AUTO-DS08] Potential Layering Activity Detected\n\n1 account(s) show patterns of 4 or more deposits within a 60-minute window. This pattern is consistent with &quot;layering&quot; — a stage of money laundering where illicit funds are broken into multiple smaller deposits in rapid succession to obscure the origin of the money and avoid triggering transaction reporting thresholds.\n\nThis is a high-severity finding that requires immediate review by the compliance team.', 'WHAT: Multiple accounts received 4 or more deposits within 60 minutes, a pattern consistent with money laundering layering.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Layering is the second stage of money laundering, where criminals break large sums into many small transactions to avoid detection. If this pattern is confirmed, the bank may be processing illicit funds and faces regulatory penalties, reputational damage, and potential criminal liability.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Immediately freeze the affected accounts pending investigation — do NOT alert the account holders. (2) Review the full transaction history of each account for the past 90 days. (3) Identify the source of funds for each deposit — are they from the same originator? (4) Cross-reference account holders against sanctions lists and PEP databases. (5) File Suspicious Transaction Reports (STR) with the relevant financial intelligence unit. (6) If confirmed, cooperate with law enforcement as required.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / AML Analyst / MLRO (Money Laundering Reporting Officer)', 'LIMBE', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-06', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-06 11:13:19'),
(167, 'HIGH', 'Transaction Monitoring', '[AUTO-C09] Large Transaction Monitoring (&gt;5,000,000 FCFA)\n\n2 large transaction(s) detected (top: TXN-20260504-0005 — 30,000,000 FCFA). Review for ML/FT compliance.', 'WHAT: Transactions exceeding 5,000,000 FCFA were detected. Large transactions require enhanced monitoring under Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: Large transactions can be indicative of money laundering, terrorist financing, or other illicit activity. Regulations require banks to monitor, document, and report such transactions.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) Review each large transaction — verify it has proper authorization, supporting documentation (invoices, contracts), and a clear business purpose. (2) Cross-reference the parties involved against sanctions lists and PEP (Politically Exposed Person) databases. (3) If the transaction appears suspicious, file a Suspicious Transaction Report (STR) with the relevant authority. (4) Ensure Large Transaction Reports (LTR) are filed as required by regulation. (5) Set up automated alerts for future transactions above this threshold.\n\nWHO: Compliance Officer / AML Analyst', 'KUMBA', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-06', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-06 11:13:21'),
(168, 'HIGH', 'Risk Management', '[AUTO-C17] Loan-to-Deposit Ratio\n\nLDR is 5.4% (loans: 1,000,000 / deposits: 18,589,008 FCFA). Below optimal range (30-90%).', 'WHAT: The Loan-to-Deposit Ratio (LDR) measures how much of the bank&#039;s customer deposits have been lent out. A healthy range is typically 30% to 90%.\n\nWHY IT MATTERS: If the LDR is above 90%, the bank may not have enough liquidity to meet withdrawal demands. If below 30%, the bank is not using its deposit base efficiently to generate interest income.\n\nHOW TO FIX: (1) If LDR is above 90%: Reduce new lending, increase deposit mobilization campaigns, or consider securitizing some loans. (2) If LDR is below 30%: Review the lending strategy for growth opportunities, relax qualifying criteria where appropriate, or launch targeted loan products. (3) Set up automated alerts when the ratio approaches 80% or drops below 35%. (4) Review the LDR monthly as part of the Asset-Liability Committee (ALCO) process.\n\nWHO: Chief Risk Officer / Treasury Manager', 'KUMBA', 'OPEN', 'Internal Audit System', '2026-05-06', 'Emmanuel Nkoulou', NULL, '2026-05-06 11:13:21');
